<section class="page-head">
  <h1>About this site</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    A hub for {{ site.college }} faculty to learn about UCF Faculty Senate committees,
    see where CECS is represented, and volunteer for open seats.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="prose">
  <h2>Why committee service matters</h2>
  <p>
    The UCF Faculty Senate staffs three classes of committees and councils — operational
    committees, curricular committees and councils, and joint university committees. They
    set policy on curriculum, budget, research, promotion and tenure, technology, the academic
    calendar, and more. When CECS faculty serve, engineering and computer science perspectives
    are part of those decisions.
  </p>

  <h2>What serving involves</h2>
  <p>
    Committee service is one of the highest-leverage, lowest-overhead forms of university
    service. Most roles ask only a few hours a semester. As a CECS representative you would:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Attend the committee's meetings</strong> — typically monthly or a few times a semester, often virtual.</li>
    <li><strong>Review and weigh in</strong> on the proposals, policies, and decisions in that committee's charge.</li>
    <li><strong>Bring the CECS perspective</strong> so engineering and computer science priorities are represented in university policy.</li>
    <li><strong>Share back</strong> anything relevant to CECS colleagues so the college stays informed.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Terms typically run two or three years. It's meaningful, citable service that strengthens
    your annual review and promotion case while growing your network across colleges.
  </p>

  <h2>How members are chosen</h2>
  <p>
    Volunteers from this site are compiled by <strong>{{ site.contactName }}</strong>
    ({{ site.contactDepartment }}), the {{ site.contactTitle }}, and put forward for nomination
    through the Faculty Senate's Committee on Committees. Volunteering expresses interest; it is
    not a guarantee of placement.
  </p>

  <h2>Your privacy</h2>
  <p>
    The volunteer form collects your name, UCF email, department, rank, committee interests, and
    optional notes. Your <strong>name and department may appear publicly</strong> on this site to
    show momentum and avoid duplicate sign-ups. Your <strong>email and notes are kept private</strong>
    and are used only by the CECS representative for follow-up.
  </p>

  <h2>How the site works</h2>
  <p>
    This is a static site hosted on GitHub Pages. Committee data lives in editable files in the
    repository. Volunteer submissions are collected through Formspree and synced back into the site
    as JSON on a schedule, so the committee pages reflect who has signed up.
  </p>

  <h2 id="ai-disclosure">AI use disclosure</h2>
  <p>
    In the spirit of honesty: development of this site — its layout, code, and much of the
    copy — was <strong>supported by generative AI technology</strong>. The <strong>data path
    remains AI-free</strong>. Committee listings, open seats, and volunteer submissions are
    entered and reviewed by people, not generated or altered by AI, and nothing you submit
    through the volunteer form is fed to an AI model.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
